% ===================== ABSTRACT =====================
\begin{abstract}
Cryptocurrency markets exhibit extreme non-stationarity, regime shifts, and volatility clustering, making traditional price prediction models unreliable for real-world trading. Existing approaches largely focus on predicting price direction while implicitly assuming continuous tradability and uniform signal reliability. In practice, professional trading systems must decide not only \emph{what} direction to trade, but also \emph{when} trading is warranted.

We propose a regime-aware meta-learning framework that explicitly separates trade eligibility from directional prediction. The system integrates heterogeneous price-based models, volatility regime classifiers, derivatives positioning signals, and macroeconomic risk regimes into a hierarchical decision architecture. A two-stage meta-model first determines market tradability and then predicts directional bias only when participation is justified. A confidence-gated execution layer further balances coverage and accuracy.

Empirical evaluation on daily Bitcoin data spanning multiple market cycles demonstrates that selective participation materially improves directional accuracy of executed trades while maintaining controlled exposure. The results highlight the importance of regime conditioning and decision-level learning in cryptocurrency markets, providing a deployable alternative to end-to-end forecasting models.
\end{abstract}

% ===================== KEYWORDS =====================
\begin{IEEEkeywords}
