% ===================== SECTION 1 =====================
\section{Introduction}
Cryptocurrency markets are characterized by extreme volatility, abrupt regime transitions, and continuous global trading. Unlike traditional financial markets, digital assets operate without centralized liquidity control and are heavily influenced by speculative capital flows. These properties severely violate the stationarity assumptions underlying most machine learning models.

Recent literature has applied deep learning architectures such as LSTMs, CNNs, and attention-based models to cryptocurrency price prediction. While many report strong statistical accuracy, their real-world utility remains limited. In live trading environments, continuous exposure to noisy or hostile regimes leads to performance decay and elevated risk.

Professional trading systems adopt layered decision-making pipelines. Rather than issuing unconditional forecasts, they decompose the trading decision into regime identification, exposure gating, directional bias estimation, and confidence assessment. This work follows that institutional philosophy.

We introduce a regime-aware, multi-stage meta-learning framework that focuses on \emph{decision quality} rather than unconditional prediction accuracy. The framework evaluates market tradability, predicts direction only when warranted, and explicitly encodes uncertainty through confidence gating.

% ===================== SECTION 2 =====================
\section{Related Work}
\subsection{Price and Return Prediction}
Early cryptocurrency forecasting relied on ARIMA and GARCH models. Later work adopted LSTM, GRU, and temporal convolutional networks. These models improve predictive accuracy but assume uniform tradability and stationarity.

\subsection{Ensemble and Meta-Learning}
Ensemble approaches combine heterogeneous predictors via voting or stacking. However, most ensembles ignore market regimes and optimize predictive loss rather than trading decisions.

\subsection{Regime Detection}
Regime-switching models and volatility-based state classifiers have been explored in financial econometrics. In crypto markets, regimes are often treated as auxiliary features rather than first-class decision constraints.

\subsection{Decision-Centric Frameworks}
Reinforcement learning agents optimize trading rewards but suffer from instability, interpretability issues, and unrealistic simulation assumptions. Our approach uses supervised learning with explicit decision decomposition.

% ===================== SECTION 3 =====================
\section{Methodology}

\subsection{Problem Formulation}
Let $P_t$ denote the Bitcoin price at time $t$ and
\begin{equation}
r_{t+1} = \frac{P_{t+1} - P_t}{P_t}
\end{equation}

Rather than predicting $r_{t+1}$ continuously, we define a decision variable:
\begin{equation}
S_t \in \{+1, -1, 0\}
\end{equation}
representing LONG, SHORT, or NO-TRADE.

The objective is:
\begin{equation}
\mathbb{E}[\text{sign}(r_{t+1}) = S_t \mid S_t \neq 0]
\end{equation}
subject to volatility, macro regime, and confidence constraints.

\subsection{Base Predictive Models}
Each base model outputs:
\begin{equation}
s_t^{(k)} \in \{-1, +1\}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Volatility Regime}
\begin{equation}
v_t =
\begin{cases}
1 & \text{High volatility} \\
0 & \text{Low volatility}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Macro Risk Regime}
\begin{equation}
m_t =
\begin{cases}
1 & \text{Risk-On} \\
0 & \text{Risk-Off}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

